About FPInnovations



FPInnovations is seeking a Research Engineer for its Transportation &amp; Infrastructure team; a group of energetic, highly skilled researchers and technicians based in Vancouver and Montreal. The team provides road engineering innovations that generates value for industrial members, provincial and federal government partners, and contracted clients. Our vision is to provide superior service to our traditional forest sector clients and extend our services to other resource and transportation sectors. Our research deals with the construction and maintenance of resource roads and water crossings, the environmental impacts of road infrastructure, the interaction between roads and heavy vehicles, road safety issues, and climate change impacts and solutions for infrastructure.

The researcher engineer will be tasked to work closely with our members and partners to develop and support delivery of our various research programs across Western Canada. They will report to the BC-based manager of the Transportation &amp; Infrastructure team in the Fibre Supply Innovation Centre of Excellence (ICE) and will work closely with other scientific, engineering, and technical research staff.



Responsibilities




The successful candidate will contribute to positive outcomes for resource road clients in one or more of the following areas:



Evaluation of innovative road subgrade construction techniques for unpaved roads;

Environmental impacts of forest road infrastructure;

Road maintenance management and life cycle costing;

General knowledge of bridge structures and geotechnical engineering;

Hydrological engineering, culvert sizing and design;

Road design and analysis of road geometry for heavy vehicle configurations;

Foundation design for drainage structures on weak soils (e.g. designing with geosynthetics and soil stabilization); and

Be a courageous safety leader; adhere to and sponsor safety and environmental rules and procedures.




Skills And Qualifications




A degree in civil, geotechnical, or forest engineering. A master’s degree would be an asset;

At least 3 years of relevant industry experience;

Hold a licensed professional engineer certification (P.Eng.), or in process;

Registered or eligible for registration with Engineers and Geoscientists BC;

Ability to work effectively in a team and independently in the field, as required; with a capacity to lead and manage field studies;

Excellent organizational, problem-solving and project management skills; a strong team player; curious and focused on improving the forest industry;

Excellent communication skills; able to prepare quality technical reports and presentations;

Fluency in English (written and spoken), French an asset;

Knowledge of road engineering programs (e.g., RoadEng, CAD) and GIS applications would be an asset; and

Willingness to travel throughout Canada and work in the field, often in remote locations, up to 20% of the time; and have a valid driver's licence.


